\section{Problem definition}

Cities are spatially interconnected systems in which access to opportunity depends on public transport,
street network structure and the distribution of destinations such as jobs and daily amenities. These
factors do not exist independently. The accessibility of one place is partly determined by what can be
reached from it and partly by the structure of its surrounding urban environment. This project studies
that interaction across ten U.S. cities using multimodal urban data and graph based machine learning.

The project combines five data sources. GTFS provides public transport supply like routes, stops and service frequencies. OpenStreetMap (OSM) and OSMNX provide amenity locations and street
network structure. LEHD/LODES provides workplace opportunity through spatially referenced job
counts. TIGER/Line provides census block boundaries, which are used to define the spatial units and
their adjacency relations. ACS provides socio demographic context that will be used after the modeling
stage to analyze which groups are concentrated in high and low accessibility neighborhoods.

The main objective is to construct a block-level accessibility and opportunity score from reachable jobs
and reachable amenities and then to test whether this score can be predicted from public-transport and
built-environment characteristics. The target is defined through \emph{reachable opportunities}, whereas the predictors mainly describe \emph{transport
supply} and \emph{urban form}. Since neighboring blocks influence each other, the project compares
both a strong non graph baseline and graph based models.

\section{Keywords}

Urban accessibility, opportunity, graph learning, GraphSAGE, graph convolutional networks, XGBoost,
explainable AI, SHAP values, GNNExplainer, census blocks, GTFS, LEHD/LODES, OSMNX.

\section{Literature review}

The literature relevant to this project can be divided into three parts: accessibility measurement,
machine learning for urban spatial analysis and graph-based explainable modeling.

First, accessibility research shows that accessibility is best understood through the opportunities that
can be reached from a location, rather than through the local presence of infrastructure alone.
\textcite{deboosere2018canadajobsaccessibility} demonstrate this clearly in their study of job
accessibility by public transport across eleven Canadian metropolitan areas. They treat workplace opportunity as a measurable spatial outcome and shows how such
an outcome can be studied in a comparative multi city setting. \textcite{gong2023parkaccessibilityhongkong} show that accessibility becomes more meaningful when it
is derived from realistic spatial indicators rather than from simple geometric assumptions. Although
their application concerns park access, the big idea is important here as well: accessibility should
be constructed from what can be reached from a neighborhood.

Second, urban machine learning research shows that multimodal spatial analysis requires careful target
construction and feature design. \textcite{casali2022spatialurbanml} provide a review of machine
learning for urban spatial analysis and show that studies in this area often combine transport,
road-network, land-use and demographic data. Their review is useful because it shows both the
potential of multimodal urban ML and the need for methodological clarity when defining targets and
predictors. This is particularly relevant for the present project, where the accessibility target is
constructed from reachable jobs and amenities, while the predictors are mainly public transport and
built environment indicators.

Third, graph-based learning provides a natural framework for modeling spatial dependence between
urban areas. \textcite{xie2025hybridspatiallearning} offer the closest methodological reference for this
project. They represent urban blocks as graph nodes, use graph neural networks to predict a block-level
urban outcome, and apply explainable AI to understand the local drivers of the predictions. Their work
shows that graph learning can capture neighborhood effects more explicitly than standard tabular
models and that local explanations are necessary if the results are to be analytically useful. For the
algorithms themselves, \textcite{hamilton2017graphsage} provide the GraphSAGE framework,
\textcite{kipf2017semi} provide the graph convolutional network (GCN), \textcite{chen2016xgboost}
provide the main non-graph baseline XGBoost, \textcite{lundberg2017unified} provide SHAP for
tabular explainability, and \textcite{ying2019gnnexplainer} provide GNNExplainer for local explanations
of graph neural networks.

Taken together, accessibility can be represented
through reachable opportunities, urban ML can integrate heterogeneous spatial datasets and graph
learning can model the spatial dependence between neighborhoods while remaining interpretable
through SHAP and GNNExplainer.

\section{Research Questions}

There are two research questions proposed in this thesis:

\textbf{RQ 1:} To what extent can XGBoost, GraphSAGE and GCN predict a block level accessibility and
opportunity score from public-transport supply and built-environment indicators across ten U.S. cities?

\textbf{RQ 2:} Which spatial factors contribute most strongly to accessibility and opportunity and how
can local explanation methods and clustering reveal recurring patterns such as transport-poor or
opportunity-poor neighborhoods?

\section{Method and Approach}

The project can be divided into five stages:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item data collection and harmonization,
    \item target construction,
    \item graph construction and predictive modeling,
    \item explainability and clustering,
    \item socio-demographic interpretation and visualization.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Study area and spatial unit}

The study covers ten U.S. cities: New York, Boston, Washington DC, Atlanta, Houston, Denver, Tulsa,
Little Rock, Santa Cruz and Los Angeles. The main spatial unit is the \textbf{census block}. Each block
becomes one observation in the tabular dataset and one node in the graph. TIGER/Line provides the
block geometry and identifiers, from which block centroids are computed.

The choice for census blocks follows the aim of keeping the analysis spatially detailed. Blocks are small
enough to reflect local transport and urban form differences, yet structured enough to be linked to
GTFS stops, OSM amenities, LEHD job counts and block adjacency. If severe sparsity or runtime
problems arise, census tracts will be the fallback unit, but the main design is based on blocks.

\subsection{Data collection and preprocessing}

The following data sources are collected for each city:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{GTFS:} public-transport schedules, stops, routes and service frequencies;
    \item \textbf{OSM/OSMNX:} street-network geometry and amenity locations;
    \item \textbf{LEHD/LODES:} workplace locations and counts;
    \item \textbf{TIGER/Line:} census-block polygons and adjacency;
    \item \textbf{ACS:} socio-demographic context variables.
\end{itemize}

The raw files are not used directly as model input. Instead, they are transformed into block-level
variables and network-based accessibility measures. All spatial layers are projected to a common
coordinate reference system. For each block, its centroid is used as the origin point for opportunity
reachability calculations. OSM street networks and GTFS stops are spatially linked to blocks. LEHD
job counts are assigned to destination blocks and later queried within distance bands around origin
blocks. ACS variables are processed separately and attached only in the final interpretation stage.

\subsection{Target construction: accessibility and opportunity score}

The supervised target is a continuous \textbf{block-level accessibility and opportunity score}. The score is
constructed from two components:
\begin{itemize}
    \item employment accessibility, based on reachable jobs;
    \item amenity accessibility, based on reachable amenities.
\end{itemize}

This target design is the key methodological choice of the project. It makes the learning problem
non-circular: the target is based on \emph{opportunities that can be reached}, whereas the predictors
mainly describe \emph{public-transport supply} and \emph{built-environment structure}.

\subsubsection{Employment accessibility}

Let \(b\) denote an origin block and \(j\) a destination block containing jobs. For a radius \(r\), the
number of reachable jobs from block \(b\) is defined as

\[
J_b(r)=\sum_{j\in\mathcal{B}} Jobs_j \cdot \mathbf{1}\!\left(d^{net}(b,j)\le r\right),
\]

where
\begin{itemize}
    \item \(\mathcal{B}\) is the set of all destination blocks in the city,
    \item \(Jobs_j\) is the number of jobs in destination block \(j\),
    \item \(d^{net}(b,j)\) is the shortest-path distance on the street network between the centroids of
    blocks \(b\) and \(j\),
    \item \(\mathbf{1}(\cdot)\) is the indicator function.
\end{itemize}

This is computed for
\[
r\in\{1,2,3,4,5\}\text{ km}.
\]

This yields five employment-accessibility values for every block.

\subsubsection{Amenity accessibility}

Amenity accessibility is defined analogously. Let \(\mathcal{A}_c\) be the set of amenities of type \(c\),
where \(c\) belongs to a fixed set of categories such as food/retail, healthcare, education, recreation,
and public services. Then the number of reachable amenities of type \(c\) from block \(b\) is

\[
M_{b,c}(r)=\sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}_c}\mathbf{1}\!\left(d^{net}(b,a)\le r\right),
\]

where \(d^{net}(b,a)\) is the shortest-path distance from the centroid of block \(b\) to amenity \(a\).

Because some amenity categories are much more common than others, counts are first normalized
within category. The amenity-accessibility component for radius \(r\) is then defined as the mean over
categories:
\[
M_b(r)=\frac{1}{|C|}\sum_{c\in C}\widetilde{M}_{b,c}(r).
\]

Again, this yields five values per block.

\subsubsection{Normalization}

The raw job and amenity counts differ strongly in scale, so all accessibility components are normalized
city by city using min--max scaling:
\[
z_{bk}=\frac{x_{bk}-\min(x_k)}{\max(x_k)-\min(x_k)}.
\]

This means the final target is interpreted as a \emph{relative within-city accessibility and opportunity
score}. The main analytical focus is therefore on spatial structure within each city and on general
patterns across cities, rather than on direct absolute comparisons of raw opportunity volume between
very different urban systems.

\subsubsection{Distance aggregation}

Closer opportunities should contribute more strongly than distant ones. Therefore, a distance-decay
weighting is applied:
\[
\alpha_1=0.30,\quad \alpha_2=0.25,\quad \alpha_3=0.20,\quad \alpha_4=0.15,\quad \alpha_5=0.10.
\]

The aggregated employment accessibility of block \(b\) is
\[
E_b=\sum_{k=1}^{5}\alpha_k \widetilde{J}_b(r_k),
\]
and the aggregated amenity accessibility is
\[
A_b=\sum_{k=1}^{5}\alpha_k \widetilde{M}_b(r_k).
\]

\subsubsection{Final target score}

The final target score is
\[
Y_b=\lambda E_b+(1-\lambda)A_b.
\]

The main specification uses equal importance for employment and amenities:
\[
Y_b=0.5E_b+0.5A_b.
\]

Two alternative specifications are used as robustness checks:
\[
Y_b^{(1)}=0.6E_b+0.4A_b,\qquad
Y_b^{(2)}=0.4E_b+0.6A_b.
\]

In addition, a sensitivity analysis will test whether conclusions remain stable under alternative radius
choices and under a reduced amenity category set. This is important because the target contains design
choices that are reasonable but not uniquely determined.

\subsection{Predictor construction}

The predictor set contains \textbf{public-transport} and \textbf{built-environment} variables. ACS variables are
deliberately excluded from the core predictive model and are used only after the modeling stage for
equity interpretation.

\paragraph{Public-transport predictors.}
From GTFS, the following block-level predictors are constructed:
\begin{itemize}
    \item stop or station count,
    \item stop density,
    \item total weekday service frequency,
    \item number of distinct routes,
    \item modal variety,
    \item average scheduled headway.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Built-environment predictors.}
From OSM/OSMNX and TIGER/Line, the following block-level predictors are constructed:
\begin{itemize}
    \item total street length density,
    \item bikeable street length density,
    \item intersection density,
    \item road-network connectivity,
    \item block compactness,
    \item land-use diversity.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Raw amenity counts are not reused as predictors}, because they
already contribute to the target through \(A_b\). This avoids leakage. Likewise, the exact job-access
variables used in the target are not reused unchanged as predictors.

The final feature vector for block \(b\) is therefore
\[
\mathbf{x}_b=[x^{PT}_{b1},\dots,x^{PT}_{bp},x^{BE}_{b1},\dots,x^{BE}_{bq}].
\]

\subsection{Graph construction}

The urban area is represented as an adjacency-only graph
\[
G=(V,E),
\]
where every census block is a node:
\[
V=\{b_1,b_2,\dots,b_n\},
\]
and an edge is added between two blocks if their polygons share a boundary:
\[
E=\{(b_i,b_j)\mid b_i \text{ and } b_j \text{ are adjacent}\}.
\]

This graph is intentionally simple. It is spatially interpretable, feasible within the thesis timeframe,
and sufficient to test whether spatial context improves prediction. Since the study covers ten cities, the
combined graph is a disconnected graph with one connected component per city.

\subsection{Predictive models}

Three regression models are used to predict \(Y_b\).

\paragraph{XGBoost.}
The first model is XGBoost, used as a strong non-graph baseline. For a dataset
\(\{(\mathbf{x}_i,y_i)\}_{i=1}^{N}\), the prediction is
\[
\hat{y}_i=\sum_{t=1}^{T} f_t(\mathbf{x}_i),
\]
where each \(f_t\) is a regression tree. The objective function is
\[
\mathcal{L}=\sum_{i=1}^{N} l(y_i,\hat{y}_i)+\sum_{t=1}^{T}\Omega(f_t),
\]
with \(l\) a regression loss and \(\Omega\) a regularization term.

\paragraph{GraphSAGE.}
The second model is GraphSAGE. For node \(v\) at layer \(k\), the update is
\[
h_v^{(k)}=
\sigma\!\left(
W^{(k)}\cdot
\mathrm{AGG}\!\left(
\{h_v^{(k-1)}\}\cup\{h_u^{(k-1)}:u\in\mathcal{N}(v)\}
\right)
\right),
\]
where \(h_v^{(0)}=\mathbf{x}_v\).

\paragraph{GCN.}
The third model is a graph convolutional network. A standard layer update is
\[
H^{(k+1)}=\sigma\!\left(\tilde{D}^{-1/2}\tilde{A}\tilde{D}^{-1/2}H^{(k)}W^{(k)}\right),
\]
where \(\tilde{A}=A+I\) is the adjacency matrix with self-loops, \(\tilde{D}\) is the corresponding degree
matrix, \(H^{(0)}=X\) and \(W^{(k)}\) are trainable parameters.

All three models operate in a regression setting and use \(Y_b\) as the target.

\subsection{Explainability and clustering}

To interpret the models:
\begin{itemize}
    \item XGBoost is explained with SHAP values;
    \item GraphSAGE and GCN are explained with GNNExplainer.
\end{itemize}

SHAP provides global and local feature contributions for the tabular baseline. GNNExplainer provides
local explanations for the graph models by identifying which node features and neighboring nodes are
most influential for a prediction.

The resulting explanation vectors are then clustered, for example with \(k\)-means, to identify recurring
spatial profiles. The aim is to move from single-block explanations to interpretable neighborhood
types, such as transport-poor blocks, street-network-limited blocks or blocks with strong
opportunities despite modest transport supply.

\subsection{ACS-based interpretation}

After the main modeling stage, ACS variables are linked to the spatial units and used for
socio-demographic interpretation. Because ACS variables are not available at true census-block level,
they will be attached through the most appropriate higher-resolution geography, such as block groups
or tracts.

The ACS stage addresses questions such as:
\begin{itemize}
    \item which groups are concentrated in the lowest accessibility deciles,
    \item whether low-accessibility areas are associated with income or demographic patterns,
    \item whether different explanation clusters correspond to different social contexts.
\end{itemize}

\section{Evaluation}

Models are evaluated with the standard regression metrics
\[
RMSE=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2},
\]
\[
MAE=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}|y_i-\hat{y}_i|,
\]
and
\[
R^2=1-\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_i-\hat{y}_i)^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{N}(y_i-\bar{y})^2}.
\]

A simple random node split would create spatial leakage, especially for the graph models. Therefore,
the main evaluation will be \textbf{spatially aware}. Within each city, blocks will be partitioned into
spatial clusters or contiguous subareas and holdout sets will be defined at that level rather than by
randomly sampling individual blocks. In addition, a leave-one-city-out experiment will be used as a
transferability test across urban environments.

Evaluation is not limited to predictive accuracy. The explanation stage is also evaluated qualitatively:
\begin{itemize}
    \item do SHAP and GNNExplainer identify plausible spatial drivers,
    \item do clustered explanation profiles correspond to interpretable neighborhood types,
    \item does the ACS-based interpretation reveal clear socio-demographic inequalities?
\end{itemize}

The project pipeline can therefore be summarized as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Data preprocessing}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Collecting GTFS, OSM/OSMNX, LEHD/LODES, ACS and TIGER/Line data.
        \item Harmonizing all sources at census-block level.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Target construction}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Computing reachable jobs within 1--5 km.
        \item Computing reachable amenities within 1--5 km.
        \item Normalizing and aggregating these into \(Y_b\).
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Feature construction}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Constructing PT predictors from GTFS.
        \item Constructing BE predictors from OSM/OSMNX and TIGER/Line.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Graph construction}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Representing census blocks as nodes.
        \item Connecting adjacent blocks with edges.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Prediction}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Training XGBoost, GraphSAGE and GCN to predict \(Y_b\).
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Explanation and clustering}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Applying SHAP and GNNExplainer.
        \item Clustering explanation profiles.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Interpretation and visualization}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Using ACS for post hoc socio-demographic interpretation.
        \item Building the prototype dashboard.
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section{Plan}

The project is divided into four phases:
exploration, implementation, evaluation, and finalizing. Writing will take place throughout the
project, so that methodological choices and intermediate results are documented while the research
is still in progress.

A milestone is placed after week 6. By then, the harmonized dataset, the final accessibility target,
and the first working model implementations should be available. If the project falls behind
schedule, the priority is to preserve the core contribution: target construction for all cities,
XGBoost and at least one graph model, one explanation method per model family, and a
lightweight dashboard.

